{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645182"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:14:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:14:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18093"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18093"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.15,0,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114543"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10807"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96544"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10254"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25169"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114543"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of tropomyosin in skeletal muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Binds calcium to initiate contraction","Stabilises the Z-disc structure","Constitutes the myosin filaments","Provides energy through ATP breakdown","Covers actin-myosin binding sites at rest"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary role of tropomyosin is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecover actin-myosin binding sites at rest\u003C/strong\u003E. During muscle activation, calcium binding to troponin causes tropomyosin to shift position, exposing these sites and enabling cross-bridge formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding calcium to initiate contraction\u003C/strong\u003E describes the role of troponin C in the regulatory complex. \u003Cstrong\u003EStabilising the Z-disc structure\u003C/strong\u003E is a structural role performed by alpha-actinin and other proteins. \u003Cstrong\u003EConstituting the myosin filaments\u003C/strong\u003E refers to how myosin molecules aggregate to form the thick filaments. \u003Cstrong\u003EProviding energy through ATP breakdown\u003C/strong\u003E describes the myosin head domain which contains the ATPase activity necessary for contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis regulatory mechanism ensures that muscle contraction occurs only when intracellular calcium levels are elevated, providing precise control of muscle activation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tropomyosin regulates muscle contraction by controlling access to binding sites on actin filaments.","In the absence of calcium, tropomyosin prevents cross-bridge formation between actin and myosin.","The position of tropomyosin on actin filaments changes with calcium-troponin binding."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology. 2nd Asia-Pacific ed. John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 6; pg. 83."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96544"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18093"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevi